Architecture plan for issues #59-#61

Scope overview
- These issues all address the same auth-login loop in the LiftFuel Expo web/native frontend and Express backend: after returning from the external MCTAI login page, the app should detect the browser cookie-backed session automatically, ensure the session cookie is accepted/sent in deployed browser contexts, and show a clear user-facing reason when session verification fails.
- Preserve the existing MCTAI `mctai_session` cookie + JWT/JWKS backend auth model. Do not introduce a parallel token or client-managed auth credential.

Module structure, file organization, shared types
- Frontend session orchestration remains in `src/features/auth/sessionService.ts`:
  - Keep `refreshSession()` as the single wrapper around `GET /api/auth/me` and local snapshot persistence.
  - Add small helpers/types here if needed to classify auth refresh outcomes for UI flows, but avoid duplicating network logic in screens.
- Frontend API error behavior remains centralized in `src/api/client.ts` and `src/api/errorMessages.ts`:
  - Preserve `credentials: 'include'` on requests so browser cookies are sent.
  - Keep status/code details on `ApiError` for development diagnostics and map common auth-login-loop failures to short non-technical messages.
- Auth UI handling belongs in `src/features/auth/screens/SignInScreen.tsx` and `src/features/auth/screens/SignUpScreen.tsx`:
  - Reuse a shared auto-refresh/check-session pattern between sign-in and sign-up where practical.
  - Keep the existing manual “Refresh session” button as a fallback.
  - Trigger session checks after opening auth, when the screen regains focus, when web `document.visibilityState` becomes visible, and when callback/query parameters indicate a return from auth.
- Root routing remains in `src/navigation/RootNavigator.tsx`:
  - `onAuthenticated` should remain the boundary that updates root auth/profile state after a successful refresh.
  - Avoid adding separate navigation states for each auth screen unless needed; keep session/profile decisions centralized.
- Backend cookie/origin work belongs in `backend/src/auth/session.ts`, `backend/src/routes/auth.ts`, `backend/src/http/origin.ts`, and `backend/src/config.ts`:
  - Keep public origin resolution proxy-aware using `X-Forwarded-Host` / `X-Forwarded-Proto` before raw `Host`.
  - If cookie options need to be generated/cleared by this backend, centralize attributes in auth/config helpers so logout clearing matches login/session cookie attributes.
  - Same-origin deployed web should use host-only cookies with `path=/`, `HttpOnly`, and `Secure` in production. Cross-site cases require `SameSite=None; Secure`; same-origin can remain `Lax` where valid.
- Documentation/config expectations should be reflected in `.env.example`:
  - `SELF_URL` and `ALLOWED_CORS_ORIGIN` should match the public app origin in deployment.
  - For deployed same-origin Expo web + API, leave `EXPO_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL` unset so frontend requests use `window.location.origin + /api`.

Dependencies between issues
- #60 should be implemented/verified first or alongside the others because no frontend refresh timing can succeed if the browser does not store/send `mctai_session` to `/api/auth/me`.
- #59 depends on the existing `refreshSession()` and root `onAuthenticated` flow. It can be implemented after #60 assumptions are clear, and should reuse current session snapshot persistence.
- #61 should be implemented after or alongside #59 so all automatic and manual refresh paths display the same classified failure messages instead of silently returning to the login page.
- Final validation should exercise all three together: external login return, focused/visible page return, manual refresh fallback, cookie presence on `/api/auth/me`, 401 handling, network/CORS failure, and 503 `AUTH_NOT_CONFIGURED` handling.

Key design decisions
- Do not hardcode any deployed hostname; derive public origin from forwarded headers/config and allow same-origin `/api` on web.
- Keep CORS and origin checks custom-domain/proxy safe: absent Origin is allowed, the public forwarded host is allowed, and configured `SELF_URL`/`ALLOWED_CORS_ORIGIN` hosts are allowed.
- Do not origin-gate static assets; only API CORS should be checked.
- Keep auth feedback concise for users but preserve specific `ApiError.status` and `ApiError.code` for logs/development.
- Avoid broad route rewrites: the likely implementation surface is small and limited to auth/session API helpers, two auth screens, root session refresh integration, and backend cookie/origin configuration docs/helpers.
